d a political environment in which an American national identity could emerge. More generally,\r\nI find that representation schemes that ignore group distinctions and use the individual as the basic unit of political representation may induce individuals to embrace a group-based notion of identity. Conversely, acknowledging group distinctions by using the group as a unit of political representation may induce individuals to embrace a more universalistic conception of identity, and thus may make group distinctions less salient.";s:13:"biblio_abst_f";s:0:"";s:16:"biblio_full_text";s:1:"0";s:15:"biblio_keywords";s:0:"";s:10:"biblio_url";s:0:"";s:10:"biblio_doi";s:0:"";s:12:"biblio_issue";s:0:"";s:19:"biblio_type_of_work";s:0:"";s:23:"biblio_accession_number";s:0:"";s:18:"biblio_call_number";s:0:"";s:12:"biblio_notes";s:0:"";s:12:"biblio_coins";s:332:"<span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Adc&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fscholar.iq.harvard.edu&amp;rft.title=From+Many%2C+One%3A+State+representation+and+the+construction+of+an+American+national+identity&amp;rft.date=2008&amp;rft.aulast=Penn&amp;rft.aufirst=Elizabeth+Maggie"></span>";s:21:"biblio_research_notes";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_custom1";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_custom2";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_custom3";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_custom4";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_custom5";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_custom6";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_custom7";s:0:"";s:19:"biblio_auth_address";s:0:"";s:21:"biblio_remote_db_name";s:0:"";s:25:"biblio_remote_db_provider";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_citekey";s:3:"123";s:12:"biblio_label";s:0:"";s:18:"biblio_access_date";s:0:"";s:16:"biblio_type_name";s:13:"Working Paper";s:4:"path";s:84:"epenn/from-many-one-state-representation-and-construction-american-national-identity";s:9:"og_groups";a:1:{i:0;i:113;}s:14:"og_groups_both";a:1:{i:113;s:5:"epenn";}s:9:"og_public";b:1;s:4:"tags";a:1:{i:6;a:2:{i:54;O:8:"stdClass":5:{s:3:"tid";s:2:"54";s:3:"vid";s:1:"6";s:4:"name";s:26:"American nationa