(130, 'scholar_bio', 'O:8:"stdClass":29:{s:3:"nid";s:3:"130";s:3:"vid";s:3:"130";s:4:"type";s:11:"scholar_bio";s:6:"status";s:1:"1";s:7:"created";s:10:"1216065734";s:7:"changed";s:10:"1216065734";s:7:"comment";s:1:"0";s:7:"promote";s:1:"0";s:6:"sticky";s:1:"0";s:18:"revision_timestamp";s:10:"1216065734";s:5:"title";s:27:"About Elizabeth Maggie Penn";s:4:"body";s:770:"Professor Penn''s areas of specialization\r\nare social choice theory, institutional organization and political\r\neconomy. She is particularly interested in the role that political\r\ninstitutions play in sparking or mitigating conflict between groups.\r\nSome of her past research has focused on the emergence of cooperation\r\nbetween individuals and groups with competing interests in dynamic\r\nsettings. Although most of her work has been theoretic, other projects\r\nhave addressed topics relating to local and state governance, including\r\nmunicipal secession and the initiative in California. Recent\r\npublications: "The Banks set in infinite spaces" and "Alternate\r\ndefinitions of the uncovered set, and their implications," both\r\nforthcoming in Social Choice and Welfare. <br>";s:6:"teaser";s:593:"Professor Penn''s areas of specialization\r\nare social choice theory, institutional organization and political\r\neconomy. She is particularly interested in the role that political\r\ninstitutions play in sparking or mitigating conflict between groups.\r\nSome of her past research has focused on the emergence of cooperation\r\nbetween individuals and groups with competing interests in dynamic\r\nsettings. Although most of her work has been theoretic, other projects\r\nhave addressed topics relating to local and state governance, including\r\nmunicipal secession and the initiative in California. Recent\r";s:3:"log";s:0:"";s:6:"format";s:1:"1";s:3:"uid";s:1:"9";s:4:"name";s:5:"epenn";s:7:"picture";s:0:"";s:4:"data";s:24:"a:1:{s:7:"contact";i:1;}";s:4:"path";s:33:"epenn/about-elizabeth-maggie-penn";s:9:"og