(226, 'biblio', 'O:8:"stdClass":83:{s:3:"nid";s:3:"226";s:3:"vid";s:3:"226";s:4:"type";s:6:"biblio";s:6:"status";s:1:"1";s:7:"created";s:10:"1224615080";s:7:"changed";s:10:"1227289612";s:7:"comment";s:1:"0";s:7:"promote";s:1:"0";s:6:"sticky";s:1:"0";s:18:"revision_timestamp";s:10:"1227289612";s:5:"title";s:87:"Using Counterfactual Models to Address Two Fallacies of Inference for Causal Mechanisms";s:4:"body";s:0:"";s:6:"teaser";s:0:"";s:3:"log";s:0:"";s:6:"format";s:1:"1";s:3:"uid";s:1:"4";s:4:"name";s:6:"aglynn";s:7:"picture";s:0:"";s:4:"data";s:24:"a:1:{s:7:"contact";i:1;}";s:11:"biblio_type";s:4:"1000";s:13:"biblio_number";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_section";s:0:"";s:19:"biblio_other_number";s:0:"";s:22:"biblio_secondary_title";s:0:"";s:21:"biblio_tertiary_title";s:0:"";s:18:"biblio_short_title";s:0:"";s:22:"biblio_alternate_title";s:0:"";s:23:"biblio_translated_title";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_authors";s:13:"Adam N. Glynn";s:24:"biblio_secondary_authors";s:0:"";s:23:"biblio_tertiary_authors";s:0:"";s:18:"biblio_corp_author";s:0:"";s:32:"biblio_other_author_affiliations";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_edition";s:0:"";s:16:"biblio_publisher";s:0:"";s:27:"biblio_original_publication";s:0:"";s:22:"biblio_reprint_edition";s:0:"";s:22:"biblio_place_published";s:0:"";s:11:"biblio_year";s:4:"2008";s:13:"biblio_volume";s:0:"";s:24:"biblio_number_of_volumes";s:0:"";s:12:"biblio_pages";s:0:"";s:11:"biblio_date";s:0:"";s:11:"biblio_isbn";s:0:"";s:11:"biblio_issn";s:0:"";s:11:"biblio_lang";s:0:"";s:13:"biblio_abst_e";s:1034:"Political scientists often cite the importance of mechanism specific causal knowledge, both for its intrinsic scientific value and as a necessity for informed policy. Counterfactual causal models provide a formal definition of mechanism specific (i.e. indirect) effects, and in this paper, I present decompositions of indirect effects to demonstrate that two common inferential heuristics can be misleading. In particular, zero (or small) average effects on one or even all legs of 