the president, learning contributes to more polarized evaluations of the president by the next election. And for those initially uncertain about the president, learning contributes to opinion formation about the president by the time he stands for reelection, and more often than not, these judgments favor the incumbent over a lesser-known challenger. Thus, in the aggregate, races with an incumbent presidential candidate are typically marked, perhaps paradoxically, by both a polarization of public opinion and an incumbency advantage.";s:13:"biblio_abst_f";N;s:16:"biblio_full_text";s:1:"0";s:15:"biblio_keywords";N;s:10:"biblio_url";N;s:10:"biblio_doi";N;s:12:"biblio_issue";N;s:19:"biblio_type_of_work";N;s:23:"biblio_accession_number";N;s:18:"biblio_call_number";N;s:12:"biblio_notes";N;s:12:"biblio_coins";s:409:"<span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Ftest2.iq.harvard.edu%2Fscholardemo&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Opinion+Formation%2C+Polarization%2C+and+Presidential+Reelection&amp;rft.date=2007&amp;rft.aulast=D.+Sunshine+Hillygus&amp;rft.aufirst=Barry+Burden&amp;rft.pub=Harvard+University&amp;rft.place=Cambridge"></span>";s:21:"biblio_research_notes";N;s:14:"biblio_custom1";N;s:14:"biblio_custom2";N;s:14:"biblio_custom3";N;s:14:"biblio_custom4";N;s:14:"biblio_custom5";N;s:14:"biblio_custom6";N;s:14:"biblio_custom7";N;s:19:"biblio_auth_address";N;s:21:"biblio_remote_db_name";N;s:25:"biblio_remote_db_provider";N;s:14:"biblio_citekey";s:3:" 27";s:12:"biblio_label";N;s:18:"biblio_access_date";N;s:16:"biblio_type_name";s:15:"Journal Article";s:4:"path";s:67:"hillygus/opinion-formation-polarization-and-presidential-reelection";s:9:"og_groups";a:1:{i:0;i:550;}s:14:"og_groups_both";a:1:{i:550;s:8:"hillygus";}s:9:"og_public";b:1;s:4:"tags";N;s:22:"last_comment_timestamp";s:10:"1236146356";s:17:"last_comment_name";N;s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";s:8:"taxonomy";a:0:{}s:5:"files";a:0:{}}'