(564, 'biblio', 'O:8:"stdClass":83:{s:3:"nid";s:3:"564";s:3:"vid";s:3:"564";s:4:"type";s:6:"biblio";s:6:"status";s:1:"1";s:7:"created";s:10:"1236146356";s:7:"changed";s:10:"1236146357";s:7:"comment";s:1:"0";s:7:"promote";s:1:"0";s:6:"sticky";s:1:"0";s:18:"revision_timestamp";s:10:"1236146357";s:5:"title";s:91:"Understanding Receptivity to Presidential Campaigns: Voter Decision-making in Election 2000";s:4:"body";s:0:"";s:6:"teaser";s:0:"";s:3:"log";s:0:"";s:6:"format";s:1:"0";s:3:"uid";s:2:"29";s:4:"name";s:8:"hillygus";s:7:"picture";s:0:"";s:4:"data";s:98:"a:3:{s:6:"submit";s:18:"Create new account";s:7:"form_id";s:13:"user_register";s:7:"contact";i:1;}";s:11:"biblio_type";s:3:"102";s:13:"biblio_number";N;s:14:"biblio_section";N;s:19:"biblio_other_number";N;s:22:"biblio_secondary_title";N;s:21:"biblio_tertiary_title";N;s:18:"biblio_short_title";N;s:22:"biblio_alternate_title";N;s:23:"biblio_translated_title";N;s:14:"biblio_authors";s:20:"D. Sunshine Hillygus";s:24:"biblio_secondary_authors";N;s:23:"biblio_tertiary_authors";N;s:18:"biblio_corp_author";N;s:32:"biblio_other_author_affiliations";N;s:14:"biblio_edition";N;s:16:"biblio_publisher";s:19:"Stanford University";s:27:"biblio_original_publication";N;s:22:"biblio_reprint_edition";N;s:22:"biblio_place_published";N;s:11:"biblio_year";s:4:"2003";s:13:"biblio_volume";N;s:24:"biblio_number_of_volumes";N;s:12:"biblio_pages";s:2:"42";s:11:"biblio_date";s:7:"03/2003";s:11:"biblio_isbn";N;s:11:"biblio_issn";N;s:11:"biblio_lang";s:3:"eng";s:13:"biblio_abst_e";s:3044:"The media pay exhaustive attention to American presidential campaigns. But while the journalists and political pundits discuss candidate blunders and campaign strategies and tactics, political science has been debating whether any of it makes a difference. The “do campaigns matter?” question has long been debated in the literature, but the more theoretically compelling research question is not ‘if’ campaigns matter, but rather, for whom and under what conditions do campaigns influence voter behavior? In pursuing these questions, this field of research will move beyond the stale and oversimplified debate about whether campaigns should be studied at all to the more politically relevant considerations about how and when campaigns influence electoral behavior. A recent renaissance of campaign research has challenged the conventional wisdom in political science that campaigns do not matter, but this literature has yet to develop a theoretical framework that explains the mechanisms by which campaign efforts influence voter behavior. Are all voters equally likely to change their vote choices in response to campaign efforts? Are some campaign activities more effective than others? My analysis helps to bridge the gap between the recent empirical work on campaign effects and the theoretical research on political persuasion and opinion change. I argue that the key to advancing our understanding of campaign effects is to recognize that voters are not tabulae rasae. Voters bring prior beliefs, affiliations, and interests with them to the context of the presidential campaign and these characteristics influence how they react to various campaign efforts. Thus, some individuals may be more or less receptive to campaign efforts — a consideration that is ignored in research looking for the single “campaign effect”. More specifically, I argue that the extent to which an individual is receptive to a presidential campaign depends on three factors: (1) stored political information, (2) long-term partisan predispositions, and (3) existing candidate support. In this paper, I show that voter decision-making is considerably more dy- 1 namic than suggested in previous research. Just a cursory look at the 2000 campaign data finds that nearly 45% of the electorate changed their vote choice at least once. More notably, I am able to offer considerable texture to the campaign effects literature by identifying the individuals for whom the campaign had the largest impact. Generally, I find that the individuals who are most likely to change their vote intentions during a presidential campaign include undecided voters, Independents, mismatched partisans (partisans supporting the candidate of the opposing party), and 3rd party supporters. Identifying the characteristics of the individuals who are up for grabs in a presidential election not only has practical political implications, but also offers theoretical insights about the mechanisms of political persuasion in the context of American presidential campaigns.";s:13:"biblio_abst_f";N;s:16:"biblio_full_text";s:1:"0";s:15:"biblio_keywords";N;s:10:"biblio_url";N;s:10:"biblio_doi";N;s:12:"biblio_issue";N;s:19:"biblio_type_of_work";N;s:23:"biblio_accession_number";N;s:18:"biblio_call_number";N;s:12:"biblio_notes";N;s:12:"biblio_coins";s:416:"<span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Ftest2.iq.harvard.edu%2Fscholardemo&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Understanding+Receptivity+to+Presidential+Campaigns%3A+Voter+Decision-making+in+Election+2000&amp;rft.date=2003&amp;rft.spage=42&amp;rft.aulast=Hillygus&amp;rft.aufirst=Sunshine&amp;rft.pub=Stanford+University"></span>";s:21:"biblio_research_notes";N;s:14:"biblio_custom1";N;s:14:"biblio_custom2";N;s:14:"biblio_custom3";N;s:14:"biblio_custom4";N;s:14:"biblio_custom5";N;s:14:"biblio_custom6";N;s:14:"biblio_custom7";N;s:19:"biblio_auth_address";N;s:21:"biblio_remote_db_name";N;s:25:"biblio_remote_db_provider";N;s:14:"biblio_citekey";s:3:" 29";s:12:"biblio_label";N;s:18:"biblio_access_date";N;s:16:"biblio_type_name";s:15:"Journal Article";s:4:"path";s:93:"hillygus/understanding-receptivity-presidential-campaigns-voter-decision-making-election-2000";s:9:"og_groups";a:1:{i:0;i:550;}s:14:"og_groups_both";a:1:{i:550;s:8:"hillygus";}s:9:"og_public";b:1;s:4:"tags";N;s:22:"last_comment_timestamp";s:10:"1236146357";s:17:"last_comment_name";N;s:13:"co