(565, 'biblio', 'O:8:"stdClass":83:{s:3:"nid";s:3:"565";s:3:"vid";s:3:"565";s:4:"type";s:6:"biblio";s:6:"status";s:1:"1";s:7:"created";s:10:"1236146356";s:7:"changed";s:10:"1236146357";s:7:"comment";s:1:"0";s:7:"promote";s:1:"0";s:6:"sticky";s:1:"0";s:18:"revision_timestamp";s:10:"1236146357";s:5:"title";s:96:"Internet Use, Interpersonal Relations and Sociability: Findings from a Detailed Time Diary Study";s:4:"body";s:0:"";s:6:"teaser";s:0:"";s:3:"log";s:0:"";s:6:"format";s:1:"0";s:3:"uid";s:2:"29";s:4:"name";s:8:"hillygus";s:7:"picture";s:0:"";s:4:"data";s:98:"a:3:{s:6:"submit";s:18:"Create new account";s:7:"form_id";s:13:"user_register";s:7:"contact";i:1;}";s:11:"biblio_type";s:3:"102";s:13:"biblio_number";N;s:14:"biblio_section";N;s:19:"biblio_other_number";N;s:22:"biblio_secondary_title";s:29:"The Internet in Everyday Life";s:21:"biblio_tertiary_title";N;s:18:"biblio_short_title";N;s:22:"biblio_alternate_title";N;s:23:"biblio_translated_title";N;s:14:"biblio_authors";s:55:"Norman H. Nie and D. Sunshine Hillygus and Lutz Erbring";s:24:"biblio_secondary_authors";N;s:23:"biblio_tertiary_authors";N;s:18:"biblio_corp_author";N;s:32:"biblio_other_author_affiliations";N;s:14:"biblio_edition";N;s:16:"biblio_publisher";s:94:"Department of Government and The Institute for Quantitative Social Sciences Harvard University";s:27:"biblio_original_publication";N;s:22:"biblio_reprint_edition";N;s:22:"biblio_place_published";N;s:11:"biblio_year";s:4:"2003";s:13:"biblio_volume";N;s:24:"biblio_number_of_volumes";N;s:12:"biblio_pages";N;s:11:"biblio_date";N;s:11:"biblio_isbn";N;s:11:"biblio_issn";N;s:11:"biblio_lang";s:3:"eng";s:13:"biblio_abst_e";s:1037:"Using exciting new time diary data, we explore the complex ways in which the Internet affects interpersonal communication and sociability. Rather than dwelling on the increasingly stale debate about whether the Internet is good or bad for sociability, we analyze when and where Internet use impacts face-to-face interactions. Internet use at home has a strong negative impact on time spent with friends and family, while Internet use at work is strongly related to decreased time with colleagues (but has little effect on social time with friends and family). Similarly, Internet use during the weekends is more strongly related to decreased time spent with friends and family than Internet use during weekdays. Our findings offer support for a “displacement” or “hydraulic” theory of Interne t use—time online is largely an asocial activity that competes with, rather than complements, face-to-face social time—but it is the location and timing of Internet use that determines which interpersonal relationships are affected.";s:13:"biblio_abst_f";N;s:16:"biblio_full_text";s:1:"0";s:15:"biblio_keywords";N;s:10:"biblio_url";N;s:10:"biblio_doi";N;s:12:"biblio_issue";N;s:19:"biblio_type_of_work";N;s:23:"biblio_accession_number";N;s:18:"biblio_call_number";N;s:12:"biblio_notes";N;s:12:"biblio_coins";s:557:"<span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Ftest2.iq.harvard.edu%2Fscholardemo&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Internet+Use%2C+Interpersonal+Relations+and+Sociability%3A+Findings+from+a+Detailed+Time+Diary+Study&amp;rft.title=The+Internet+in+Everyday+Life&amp;rft.date=2003&amp;rft.aulast=Erbring&amp;rft.aufirst=Norman+Nie+and+Sunshine+Hillygus+and+Lutz&amp;rft.pub=Department+of+Government+and+The+Institute+for+Quantitative+Social+Sciences+Harvard+University"></span>";s:21:"biblio_research_notes";N;s:14:"biblio_custom1";N;s:14:"biblio_custom2";N;s:14:"biblio_custom3";N;s:14:"biblio_custom4";N;s:14:"biblio_custom5";N;s:14:"biblio_custom6";N;s:14:"biblio_custom7";N;s:19:"biblio_auth_address";N;s:21:"biblio_remote_db_name";N;s:25:"biblio_remote_db_provider";N;s:14:"biblio_citekey";s:3:" 37";s:12:"biblio_label";N;s:18:"biblio_access_date";N;s:16:"biblio_type_name";s:15:"Journal Article";s:4:"path";s:98:"hillygus/internet-use-int